2005-01-11: SQLCMD: Do not report long tokens as a problem in general.

Version 77.00
-------------
2005-01-04: Version 77.00 released.
2005-01-03: SQLCMD: Support SQLCMDPASSWORDS environment variable,
            analogous to INFOTPASS in infotables program, which is
            available at the IIUG and was written by Ravikrishna
            (rkusenet@sympatico.ca), after prodding.  The semantics are
            slightly different - if you specify "sqlcmd -u me -d mine",
            SQLCMD will ignore the entry 'mine|you|yours' because it is
            for the wrong user (but AFAICT infotables would use that
            entry, connecting as 'you').
2004-12-25: Various refactorizations of headers to permit development of
            'adhoc' on machines without CSDK.
2004-12-08: SQLUNLOAD: Add -O orderby option.
2004-12-03: Revise FAQ.html to discuss 64-bit builds on Solaris, and
            indirectly on other non-natively 64-bit platforms.  Issue
            raised by Jinming Xiao <jxiao@us.ibm.com> on attempting to
            compile SQLCMD with a 64-bit platform.

Version 76.00
-------------
2004-10-15: Version 76.00 released.
2004-10-14: Pablo León <pablo.leon@horus.es> added '-u username -p
            password' support to the *blob programs -- thanks, Pablo.

Version 75.00
-------------
2004-08-25: Version 75.00 released.
2004-08-24: CONFIGURE: Accommodate CSDK 2.90 which contains ESQL/C 2.90,
            not 9.54 as you would expect.  Most source code should not test
            ESQLC_VERSION; only headers such as esqlc.h may use it.
2004-08-17: SQLCMD: LOAD handles DB-Access style backslash-space data for
            empty, non-null VARCHAR, NVARCHAR, LVARCHAR fields.  Found bug
            B169213 (ifx_var_setdata() does not permit zero-length values);
            workaround in place.  Also found B169309 (insert cursors do not
            handle zero-length non-null VARCHAR<->NVARCHAR conversions
            properly); no workaround devised yet (known BUG in SQLCMD).
2004-08-04: SQLCMD: UNLOAD generates DB-Access style backslash-space output
            for empty, non-null VARCHAR, NVARCHAR and LVARCHAR values.
            (Requested by Ravi <rkusenet@sympatico.ca>; previously known
            defect - for compatibility with DB-Access.)
2004-06-29: SQLCMD: Do not silently ignore history commands when history
            turned off.

