Version 66
----------
2001-10-01: Version 66 released.
2001-10-01: SQLCMD: Fix core dump and other context problems handling XML
            record tag.  Fix uninitialized benchmark status stack.  Make
            use of STRDUP macro consistent - return value is not checked.
2001-09-30: Add SELMULTIBLOB example blob manipulation program.
2001-09-30: SQLCMD: Add new grammar.h, grammar.y to distribution, even
            though they are currently unused.  They provide an indication
            of what will happen to LOAD, UNLOAD, RELOAD and UPLOAD, but
            nothing is carved in stone as yet.  Note that one probable
            option is to add the SQLCMD built-in commands to the grammar
            too -- providing a level of checking (and options) that are not
            currently available.  For example: "output to /tmp/x3" writes
            to a file called "to", rather than generating an error.
2001-09-29: SQLCMD: Use new library functions to convert C character/string
            literals to corresponding characters - for EOR, Quote, Escape,
            Delimiter.  Use quotify() in sqlcmd.c to allow sloppy command
            line arguments.
2001-09-09: SQLCMD: Add code to handle EOR delimiters.  Fix bug such that
            "delim;" did not print delimiter and did set delimiter to
            semi-colon.  Broken backwards compatibility: character for
            quote, escape, delim commands must be in quotes.
2001-09-09: Add SELBLOB and APPBLOB example blob manipulation programs.
2001-09-04: SQLCMD: Separate structure for CONNECT from INFO from LOAD.
2001-09-03: SQLCMD: *INTERFACE CHANGE* Rename -h (history) option to -y.
            The new -h option is for help, and shows the program version
            information, the summary usage, and a succinct description of
            each option.  Reserve option flags for integrating SQLUPLOAD
            into SQLCMD; there will be changes compared with SQLUPLOAD as
            a free-standing program.
2001-09-02: SQLCMD: Add INFO CHECK CONSTRAINTS.
2001-09-01: SQLCMD: Upgrade INFO TABLES, INFO SYSTABLES and INFO SYNONYMS
            to include table type information.
2001-08-30: SQLCMD: Implement INFO STATUS and INFO FRAGMENTS.
2001-08-30: SQLCMD: Reject handling XML input for LOAD as too difficult to
            handle sensibly.  Generally, programs should be strict in what
            they generate as output and relaxed in what they accept as
            input.  However, amongst other things, handling XML input means
            that the code must accept <R><D1>v1a</D1><D2>v2a</D2></R> in
            one record and <R><D2>v2b</D2><D1>v1b</D1></R> in the next; the
            field names have to be accepted in any order (especially since
            they are unambiguously tagged).  The code should generate NULLs
            for any missing tags.  It must generate errors on unexpected
            tags.  The LOAD code is set up to scan rigidly formatted data.
            The new code for reading XML would need to skip attributes on
            tags, ignore embedded white space (including newlines) between
            tags, handle stuff not enclosed in the record tag, handle
            missing record tags, handle duplicate field tags, decode HTML
            escapes, and so on.  Therefore, the pseudo-XML generated by
            SQLCMD is an output-only option.  Someone can write some input
            transforming program to deal with converting from XML data to
            Informix LOAD format, possibly in Perl.  And the LOAD commands
            in SQLCMD will reject the request if the format is XML.
2001-08-29: SQLCMD: Allow for comments before built-in commands.  Also
            recognize #! as a comment so '#!/usr/bin/sqlcmd -xddbname' on
            the first line of a script works.  The (Linux 2.2.x) kernel
            executes sqlcmd with the argument -xddbname (enabling trace and
            selecting the database called dbname), followed by the script
            file name (prefixed with path), followed by any command line
            arguments.  DB-Access cannot do this because neither it nor the
            database server recognizes the #! line as a comment.
2001-08-26: SQLCMD: Remove sqlcfg.h (replaced by estrdup.c and emalloc.h).
2001-08-25: UNLOAD FORMAT: revise document to account for DB-Access -X
            option and empty, non-null VARCHAR values.
2001-08-25: SQLCMD: Remove support for blobinfile command and -b option
            prior to introducing extended versions of the LOAD, RELOAD,
            UNLOAD (and UPLOAD) statements to SQLCMD.
2001-08-24: SQLCMD: Upgrade INFO to allow WHERE clauses on general queries
            (rather than table-specific queries): INFO TABLES, SYNONYMS,
            ROLES, USERS, PROCEDURES, VIEWS, BASETABLES, SYSTABLES.  Report
            on SQL executed for INFO statements when tracing is on.
2001-08-23: SQLCMD: Do not log history to readline history until command
            expansion complete.  Support PASSWORD as equivalent of USING in
            CONNECT.  Allow EXECUTE FUNCTION as well as EXECUTE PROCEDURE
            in UNLOAD.

